${\footnote Setting Shape of Mouse Cursor}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Setting Shape of Mouse Cursor;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
\{bmc IDF20404.bmp\} Setting Shape of Mouse Cursor\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Mouse}{\v 20234}\par
\par
\{bmc IDF20404.bmp\} \b \i setting shape of mouse cursor \i0 \b0  \par
\tab \{bmc IDF20405.bmp\} \b \i picture of mouse cursor (default = original) \i0 \b0 \par
\tab \{bmc IDF20406.bmp\} \b \i horizontal X coordinate of the region beginning \i0 \b0 \par
\tab \{bmc IDF20407.bmp\} \b \i vertical Y coordinate of the region beginning \i0 \b0 \par
\tab \{bmc IDF20408.bmp\} \b \i width of region \i0 \b0 \par
\tab \{bmc IDF20409.bmp\} \b \i height of region \i0 \b0 \par
\par
The \b \i setting shape of mouse cursor \i0 \b0 element serves to redefine the mouse cursor shape dependent on various locations in the program window. As parameters a variable of the item type with a mouse cursor picture, the sheet origin coordinates and the sheet dimensions can be entered. In the picture definition the colors will be interpreted as follows:\par
\par
\b \cf13 XXX \cf0 transparent \b0 \tab - transparent \par
\b \cf15 XXX \cf0 white color \b0 \tab - white \par
\b \cf0 XXX \cf0 black color \b0 \tab - black \par
\b \cf9 XXX \cf0 red color  \b0 \tab - inversion \par
\b \cf11 XXX \cf0 yellow color \b0 \tab - inversion + hot spot \par
\b \cf2 XXX \cf0 dark green \b0 \tab - black + hot spot \par
\b \cf10 XXX \cf0 light green \b0 \tab - white + hot spot \par
\b \cf12 XXX \cf0 blue color \b0 \tab - transparent + hot spot \par
\par
A hot spot designates the mouse cursor active location. This is a point to which the mouse cursor coordinates are related. If not redefined, the hot spot default position is the mouse cursor picture center. An inversion means the inversion of the color below the mouse cursor.\par
\par
If a mouse cursor picture omits or the {\uldb sheet border}{\v 20249} element is used, a standard mouse cursor (an arrow usually) will be used in the specified area.  If the sheet origin coordinates are not specified, then 0 coordinates will be used; if the area dimensions are not specified, then unlimited area dimensions are used. A standard mouse cursor setting can thus be attained by specifying the mouse cursor shape without any parameter.\par
\par
The number of areas for defining the mouse cursor shape can be arbitrary. The old areas can be redefined by overlaying them with a new one.\par
\page

